	<title>What is Quantum Calculus</title>

	<category term="Mathematics" />

	<content type="xhtml">
		<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
			<div class="quote">
				<blockquote>
					<p>
						Consider the following expression:
					</p>
					<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
						<mfrac>
							<mrow>
								<mrow>
									<mi>f</mi>
									<mo>(</mo>
									<mi>x</mi>
									<mo>)</mo>
								</mrow>
								<mo>-</mo>
								<mrow>
									<mi>f</mi>
									<mo>(</mo>
									<msub>
										<mi>x</mi>
										<mn>0</mn>
									</msub>
									<mo>)</mo>
								</mrow>
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								<mi>x</mi>
								<mo>-</mo>
								<msub>
									<mi>x</mi>
									<mn>0</mn>
								</msub>
							</mrow>
						</mfrac>
					</math>
					<p>
						As
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mi>x</mi>
						</math>
						approaches
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<msub>
								<mi>x</mi>
								<mn>0</mn>
							</msub>
						</math>,
						the limit, if it exists, gives the familiar definition of the derivative
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mfrac>
								<mrow>
									<mi>d</mi>
									<mi>f</mi>
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									<mi>d</mi>
									<mi>x</mi>
								</mrow>
							</mfrac>
						</math>
						of a function
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mrow>
								<mi>f</mi>
								<mo>(</mo>
								<mi>x</mi>
								<mo>)</mo>
							</mrow>
						</math>
						at
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mrow>
								<mi>x</mi>
								<mo>=</mo>
								<msub>
									<mi>x</mi>
									<mn>0</mn>
								</msub>
							</mrow>
						</math>.
						However, if we take 
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mrow>
								<mi>x</mi>
								<mo>=</mo>
								<mn>q</mn>
								<mo>&#8290;</mo>
								<msub>
									<mi>x</mi>
									<mn>0</mn>
								</msub>
							</mrow>
						</math>.
						or
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mrow>
								<mi>x</mi>
								<mo>=</mo>
								<msub>
									<mi>x</mi>
									<mn>0</mn>
								</msub>
								<mo>+</mo>
								<mn>h</mn>
							</mrow>
						</math>.
						where
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mn>q</mn>
						</math>
						is a fixed number different than
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mn>1</mn>
						</math>,
						and 
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mn>h</mn>
						</math>
						a fixed number different from
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mn>0</mn>
						</math>,
						and do not take the limit, we enter the fascinating world of quantum calculus:
						The corresponding expressions are the definitions of <em>q</em>-derivative and <em>h</em>-derivative of
						<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
							<mrow>
								<mi>f</mi>
								<mo>(</mo>
								<mi>x</mi>
								<mo>)</mo>
							</mrow>
						</math>.
						Beginning with these two definitions [...] two types of quantum calculus, the <em>q</em>-calculus and <em>h</em>-calculus [are developed].
					</p>
				</blockquote>
				<p class="quote-by">
					-- <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www-math.mit.edu/~kac/">Victor G. Kac</a>
					 , <a rel="nofollow" href="http://maths.dept.shef.ac.uk/maths/staff_info.php?id=459"> Pokman Cheung</a>
				</p>
				<p class="quote-from">
					from "Quantum Calculus"
				</p>
			</div> <!-- class="quote" -->
		</div>
	</content>
